const processData = () => {
  for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
    const percentage = ((parseFloat(data[i].sum) - min) / range) * 100;
    data[i].value = percentage;
  }
};

processData();
console.log(data);
```

После выполнения этого кода, массив `data` будет содержать процентное значение для каждого элемента.

To enable fullscreen mode with Vulkan, you can follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have installed the appropriate Vulkan SDK and have set up your development environment correctly.

2. When creating the Vulkan window, you can use the GLFW library. GLFW provides a simple way to create a window with Vulkan support, and it helps to enable the fullscreen mode. If you don't have GLFW installed, you can download it from the official website: https://www.glfw.org/download.html. Make sure to choose the correct version for your operating system.

3. When initializing GLFW and creating the window, you must set the appropriate window hint for Vulkan support:

```c
    // Initialize GLFW
    if (!glfwInit())
    {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to initialize GLFW\n");
        return -1;
    }

    // Enable Vulkan surface
    glfwWindowHint(GLFW_CLIENT_API, GLFW_NO_API);
```

4. To enable fullscreen mode, you can retrieve the primary monitor and its video mode by calling `glfwGetPrimaryMonitor()` and `glfwGetVideoMode()`, and then create a window with the video mode's dimensions. Here is the example code:

```c
    const GLFWvidmode* mode = glfwGetVideoMode(glfwGetPrimaryMonitor());

    // Create a fullscreen window
    GLFWwindow* window = glfwCreateWindow(mode->width, mode->height, "My Vulkan Fullscreen Application", glfwGetPrimaryMonitor(), nullptr);
    if (window == NULL)
    {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to open GLFW window.\n");
        glfwTerminate();
        return -1;
    }
```

5. Next, set up Vulkan, create a Vulkan instance and surface, and configure the application. You can follow guides and tutorials available online to set up the Vulkan like the official Vulkan Tutorial website: https://vulkan-tutorial.com/.

6. In your main loop, poll for events and render your application:

```c
    while (!glfwWindowShouldClose(window))
    {
        glfwPollEvents();

        // Vulkan rendering code here
    }
```

7. Don't forget to clean up your Vulkan objects and the GLFW window before exiting:

```c
    // Clean up Vulkan objects here

    glfwDestroyWindow(window);
    glfwTerminate();

    return 0;
```

Now, when you run your application, it will display in fullscreen mode using Vulkan.

