To render server-side-rendered content dynamically, you can use the `fetch` function to make an HTTP request to retrieve the desired content and then update the innerHTML of the target div.

First, create an API to serve your server-side-rendered content. For this example, let's assume you have an API endpoint at `https://yourserver.com/api/ssr` that returns the render HTML.

Create a JavaScript function to fetch the server-side-rendered content and insert it into the target div:

```javascript
// Function to get SSR content and insert it into the target div
async function loadSsrContent() {
  // Fetch the server-side-rendered content from the API endpoint
  const response = await fetch('https://yourserver.com/api/ssr');

  // If the fetch is successful, update the innerHTML of the target div
  if (response.ok) {
    const ssrContent = await response.text();
    document.getElementById('ssr').innerHTML = ssrContent;
  } else {
    console.error('Error fetching SSR content:', response.status, response.statusText);
  }
}
```

When you want to load the server-side-rendered content, call this function:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  // Load the SSR content when the page is loaded
  loadSsrContent();
});
```

